###############--LEAKS--###################

/bin/echo ""'totally logical'""  #ok

ls -l | awk '$1 ~ /^d/ {print $9}' #ok

< > #ok


##############--STD_OUT--##################

export T="|"
echo segfault $T grep segfault

export T='|'
echo segfault $T grep segfault

export T=">"
echo segfault $T grep segfault

export T='<'
echo segfault $T grep segfault

export T="<<"
echo segfault $T grep segfault

export T='<<'
echo segfault $T grep segfault

##############--SIGNALS--###################

ctrl-C in an empty prompt should display a new line with a new prompt. # ok
ctrl-\ in an empty prompt should not do anything. # wrong
ctrl-D in an empty prompt should quit minishell # exitcode 1 instead of 0 >> 2 instead of 0
ctrl-C in a prompt after you wrote some stuff should display a new line with a new prompt. # ok
The buffer should be clean too. Press "Enter" to make sure nothing from the previous line is executed. # ok
ctrl-D in a prompt after you wrote some stuff should not do anything. # ok
ctrl-\ in a prompt after you wrote some stuff should not do anything. # wrong
Try ctrl-C after running a blocking command like cat without arguments or grep “something“. # exitcode 0 instead of 130
Try ctrl-\ after running a blocking command like cat without arguments or grep “something“. # exitcode 0 instead of 131 (Core dumped)
Try ctrl-D after running a blocking command like cat without arguments or grep “something“. # ok